	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I know that they're there because they reused the same logic that fetches background data to fetch sprite data. Since sprites don't need name/attribute table information, garbage is read for those before the patterns are read. I have no idea whether there's any logic to the address used for the garbage fetches.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>kyuusaku</b> [ Mon Mar 26, 2012 2:20 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Has the pixel-access relationship even been truly confirmed? Some of the observed timing doesn't make a lot of sense to me and it seems like a really difficult thing to test since the PPU doesn't have way to capture digital pixels so one must use a scope and logic analyzer simultaneously, and probably write a test ROM for predictable video that can be triggered..
<br />
<br />This might be something that will be best understood through better die photos.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Mon Mar 26, 2012 5:44 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">the PPU doesn't have way to capture digital pixels</div>
<br />Fortunately, available tools make it easy to develop and run such a test ROM as long as it doesn't rely on the power-up state. Then in your test ROM, stick to monochrome video ($0F, $30) and sync to the master clock, and it might be possible to make PPU output "look digital" to a logic analyzer. Or are the levels all wrong for this?
<br />
<br />But what people are eager to learn are how the addresses for the garbage nametable fetches are constructed.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>kyuusaku</b> [ Mon Mar 26, 2012 6:58 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The levels aren't right, but video can be put through a high-speed comparator to detect a specific level perhaps. That's still a difficult setup in my opinion. I think the most accessible solution would be to use the PowerPak as a logic analyzer; a mapper could be designed to detect a particular pattern read, then count the remaining /RD rising edges until the CPU receives a NMI/PPU stops rendering at Vblank. The mapper could also feed the PPU different values irrespective of being the same address to determine which reads are actually garbage.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


